---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Papers — Agents of Chaos"
  description="An interactive relevance graph of papers we're reading. Nodes are papers, edges are relevance, and a vertex-nomination slider surfaces what to read next."
>
  <div class="page-head">
    <h1>Papers</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A relevance graph of what we're reading — and a principled guess at what to read next.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="reading">
    <span class="section-label"><span class="num">01</span>/ the graph</span>
    <p>
      Every node is a paper; every edge is <b>relevance</b>. The heaviest edge from a
      paper points at its most-related neighbour, because the weight is led by the cosine
      of the papers' <a href="https://www.semanticscholar.org/product/api" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SPECTER2</a>
      embeddings and sharpened by shared references. Hover a paper to light up what it's
      close to; drag the slider to let the graph nominate unread papers.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="graph-wrap">
    <div class="controls">
      <div class="ctl ctl-slider">
        <label for="discover">Discover <span class="ctl-k" id="discover-k">—</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="discover" min="0" max="100" value="0" step="1" />
        <span class="ctl-hint">unread papers, ranked by relevance to your set</span>
      </div>
      <div class="ctl ctl-add">
        <label for="add-id">Add a paper</label>
        <div class="add-row">
          <input type="text" id="add-id" placeholder="arXiv id, DOI, or S2 id" autocomplete="off" spellcheck="false" />
          <button id="add-btn" type="button">add</button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="ctl ctl-actions">
        <button id="export-btn" type="button" title="download the current graph as papers.json">export</button>
        <button id="reset-btn" type="button" title="forget papers you added locally">reset</button>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div id="papers-graph"></div>
    <div class="graph-foot">
      <span id="graph-status">loading…</span>
      <span class="graph-legend">
        <span class="lg-dot lg-read"></span> in your set
        <span class="lg-dot lg-ghost"></span> nominated · click to keep
      </span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="reading">
    <span class="section-label"><span class="num">02</span>/ what to read next</span>
    <h2>Vertex nomination</h2>
    <p>
      Given the papers you've read, which unread papers should you read? That's a named
      problem — <em>vertex nomination</em> — from the random-graph statistics literature.
      The principle: a candidate is relevant if it sits close to <em>any</em> paper you've
      already read. We score each candidate by its nearest-read cosine in embedding space
      (the simplest consistent member of the spectral-nomination family, robust to a
      reading list that spans several distinct threads) and reveal the ranking in order.
      The slider above is a window onto this list; the rows below are the same list, with
      a relative-relevance score and the paper that pulled each one in.
    </p>
    <div id="readlist" class="readlist"></div>
  </div>

  <div class="reading">
    <span class="section-label"><span class="num">03</span>/ relatedness</span>
    <h2>How an edge is defined</h2>
    <p>
      Hover any node and the graph shades every other paper by predicted relatedness:
    </p>
    <p class="formula">
      w(i, j) = 0.65 · cos(eᵢ, eⱼ) + 0.25 · shared-references + 0.10 · direct-citation
    </p>
    <p>
      The embedding cosine is the only term that's always defined, so it sets each paper's
      nearest neighbour; the citation terms can only sharpen the ranking, never invent it.
      One wrinkle worth being honest about: SPECTER2 cosines between in-field papers sit in
      a narrow, high band — everything is <em>somewhat</em> similar — so the structure comes
      from <em>k</em>-nearest-neighbours (scale-invariant) and the hover shading is stretched
      across the range you're actually looking at, not an absolute scale. It's the difference
      between "related" and "more related than the rest," which is the question you care about.
    </p>
    <p class="src-note">
      Papers, embeddings, and recommendations from
      <a href="https://www.semanticscholar.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Semantic Scholar</a>.
      Papers you add live in your browser; <b>export</b> writes a <code>papers.json</code> you can
      commit to make them part of the public graph.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .graph-wrap {
    margin: 1.4rem 0 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: 1.1rem 0 0.9rem;
  }
  .controls {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: flex-end;
    gap: 1.6rem 2.2rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.9rem;
  }
  .ctl label {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    font-variant: small-caps;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
  }
  .ctl-k { color: var(--muted-2); letter-spacing: 0.04em; margin-left: 0.3rem; }
  .ctl-slider { flex: 1 1 280px; min-width: 240px; }
  .ctl-slider input[type="range"] { width: 100%; accent-color: var(--accent); cursor: pointer; }
  .ctl-slider input[type="range"]:disabled { opacity: 0.45; cursor: default; }
  .ctl-hint { display: block; font-size: 0.72rem; font-style: italic; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 0.2rem; }
  .add-row { display: flex; gap: 0.4rem; }
  #add-id {
    font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.8rem; padding: 0.35rem 0.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule); background: #fff; color: var(--fg); width: 16rem; max-width: 52vw;
  }
  #add-id:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent); }
  .controls button {
    font-family: var(--font); font-size: 0.82rem; font-variant: small-caps; letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    padding: 0.35rem 0.8rem; border: 1px solid var(--accent); background: var(--bg); color: var(--accent);
    cursor: pointer; transition: background 0.15s ease, color 0.15s ease;
  }
  .controls button:hover { background: var(--accent); color: var(--bg); }
  .ctl-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; }
  .ctl-actions button { border-color: var(--rule); color: var(--muted); }
  .ctl-actions button:hover { border-color: var(--accent); background: var(--bg); color: var(--accent); }

  #papers-graph {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    height: 560px;
    background:
      radial-gradient(circle at 1px 1px, rgba(0,0,0,0.035) 1px, transparent 0) 0 0 / 22px 22px,
      var(--bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-soft);
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  #papers-graph :global(svg) { display: block; width: 100%; height: 100%; }
  #papers-graph :global(.node-label) {
    font-family: var(--font); font-size: 10.5px; fill: #4a463f;
    paint-order: stroke; stroke: var(--bg); stroke-width: 3px; stroke-linejoin: round;
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .graph-tip {
    position: absolute; display: none; z-index: 5; max-width: 280px;
    background: #fffdf6; border: 1px solid var(--rule); box-shadow: 0 4px 14px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
    padding: 0.45rem 0.6rem; font-size: 0.8rem; line-height: 1.3; pointer-events: none;
  }
  .graph-tip strong { display: block; color: var(--fg); margin-bottom: 0.15rem; font-weight: 600; }
  .graph-tip span { color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.72rem; }

  .graph-foot {
    display: flex; justify-content: space-between; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.5rem;
    margin-top: 0.55rem; font-size: 0.74rem; color: var(--muted);
  }
  #graph-status { font-style: italic; }
  .graph-legend { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.45rem; }
  .lg-dot { width: 9px; height: 9px; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; margin-left: 0.6rem; }
  .lg-read { background: #37332e; }
  .lg-ghost { background: var(--bg); border: 1.3px dashed #b9b09a; }

  .readlist { margin-top: 1rem; }
  .rl-empty { color: var(--muted); font-style: italic; font-size: 0.92rem; }
  .rl-row {
    display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1.4rem 1fr 2.2rem auto; align-items: baseline; gap: 0.6rem;
    padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-soft);
  }
  .rl-rank { color: var(--muted-2); font-size: 0.8rem; font-variant: small-caps; }
  .rl-main a { font-size: 0.98rem; }
  .rl-meta { display: block; font-size: 0.73rem; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 0.1rem; }
  .rl-rel { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--accent); text-align: right; }
  .rl-add {
    font-family: var(--font); font-size: 0.72rem; font-variant: small-caps; letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule); background: var(--bg); color: var(--muted); padding: 0.2rem 0.5rem; cursor: pointer;
  }
  .rl-add:hover { border-color: var(--accent); color: var(--accent); }

  .formula {
    font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--fg);
    background: var(--accent-soft); border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 0.55rem 0.8rem; margin: 0.4rem 0 0.9rem; overflow-x: auto;
  }
  .src-note { font-size: 0.84rem; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 1.2rem; }
  .src-note code { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.86em; }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    #papers-graph { height: 440px; }
    .rl-row { grid-template-columns: 1.2rem 1fr auto; }
    .rl-rel { display: none; }
  }
</style>

<script>
  import { initPapersGraph } from "../scripts/papers-graph";
  initPapersGraph();
</script>
